
** PL/SQL objects

  - package
  - package body
  - type
  - type ... as object
  - function
  - procedure
  - trigger

** Errors

  <example>
    SQL> show errors procedure <name>
  </example>


** Packages

  - OraclePlsqlPackages

** Built-in Functions

  - OraclePlsqlBuiltin

** Functions versus Procedures

  - Use the *call* command in sqlplus to perform a procedure. A
    function can only be executed inside a sql statedment or inside a
    PL/SQL block.

  <example>
    select fact(3) from dual;
    begin
      num := fact(3);
    end;
  </example>


** Output

  - Enabling of *serveroutput* should be enabled for each executed
    statement.

  <example><verbatim>
    set serveroutput on;
    ...
    dbms_output.put_line( 'Test of Foo' );
    ..
  </verbatim></example>
  
** Trigger

  - *:new* and *:old* are pseudo records

** Cursor

  - cur%rowtype
  - cur%notfound

** SQL Cursor

  A implicit cursor for the sql engine. It returns useful information
  about the recently executed sql statement.

  - sql%found
  - sql%isopen		always false for implicit cursors
  - sql%notfound
  - sql%rowcount
  - sql%bulk_rowcount

** Attributes

  - constant
  - not null
  - *%type*, takes the type of a previously defined type.
  - *%rowtype*, takes the type of a database table.

** Control

  - null

  - if then ... else ... end if
  - case when ... then ... end case

  - loop ... end loop
  - loop ... exit ... end loop
  - loop ... exit when ... end loop
  - loop ... exit <<loop label>>> ... end loop

  - while ... <loop>
  - for num in 1..10 <loop>
  - for rec in cur <loop>

** Exception

  - = no_data_found =
  - OraclePlsqlExceptions
s

** Quoting

  - If a table contains a attribute that is equal a PL/SQL reserved
    word then the attribute needs to be quoted in the SQL statement.

  <example>
     select name, "type" from abc;
  </example>

** Types

  - Subtype
  - Collections OraclePlsqlColl
  - Objects OraclePlsqlObjects

** Delimiters

  - % attribute indicator
  - : host variable idicator
  - " quoted identifier
  - := assignment
  - => association
  - ** exponentation
  - <<>> label

** Pragmas

  - autonomous_transaction
  - restrict_refereneces
  - exception_init

** Dynamic SQL

  - OraclePlsqlDyn

** Not Supported

  - *decode* not supported on Oracle 8.

** Hide Source Code

  - Look for the wrap utility.

** Different Schemas

Normally the plsql code runs with the privileges who creates the
procedure, function or package (definer's rights). To run it under the
user rights (invoker's rights) it's neccessary to use "authid current
user". Default is "authid definer".
